## 6. Data Model (ERD)

The pipeline produces a relational model in Silver and analytics tables in Gold.

![ERD Diagram](docs/erd.png)

### Silver — Dimensions

**`silver.dim_customers`** (5,000 rows) — One row per customer.
- Personal info: name, email, phone, date_of_birth, gender, nationality
- Geography: country, city, lat, lon
- Derived: `age`, `age_bucket`, `tenure_months`, `risk_bucket`, `credit_score_bucket`
- Segmentation: `customer_segment`, `kyc_status`, `status`, `risk_score`
- Credit info: `credit_score`, `utilization_pct`, `total_limit`, `late_payments_12m`
- Digital engagement: `mobile_app_registered`, `preferred_channel`, `last_login_date`

**`silver.dim_accounts`** (17,529 rows) — One row per account.
- `account_id`, `customer_id`, `account_type`, `currency`
- `balance_local`, `balance_usd`, `credit_limit_local`, `credit_limit_usd`
- `interest_rate`, `opened_date`, `status`, `branch_code`

### Silver — Facts

**`silver.fct_transactions`** (~85,000 rows) — One row per transaction.
- `transaction_id`, `customer_id`, `account_id`, `transaction_date`
- `amount_local`, `amount_usd`, `currency`, `transaction_type`, `category`, `channel`
- Flags: `is_failed`, `is_international`
- Derived: `day_of_week`, `month_num`, `year_num`

**`silver.fct_loans`** (7,663 rows) — One row per loan.
- `loan_id`, `customer_id`, `loan_type`, `currency`
- `principal_usd`, `outstanding_balance_usd`, `interest_rate`, `term_months`
- `loan_status`, `days_past_due`, `dpd_bucket`, `is_delinquent`

### Gold — Analytics Tables

Each Gold table is built to answer a specific dashboard page.

| Table | Grain | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| `gold_executive_overview` | One row per customer | KPIs, AUM, acquisition trend |
| `gold_revenue_transactions` | One row per transaction | Revenue, channels, categories |
| `gold_risk_credit` | One row per loan | Risk, delinquency, credit scoring |
| `gold_customer_engagement` | One row per account | Demographics, digital adoption |

---

## 7. PySpark Logic

The script `spark/flatten_bronze.py` runs inside the Airflow container and performs:

### Reading Bronze

Uses JDBC to read `bronze.raw_fintech_data`, then parses the `data` JSONB column into a typed structure using an explicit schema (`get_bronze_schema()`).

### Flattening Arrays

| Source array | Output table | Result |
|---|---|---|
| `accounts[]` | `silver.stg_accounts` | 17,529 rows |
| `transactions[]` | `silver.stg_transactions` | 85,067 rows |
| `loans[]` | `silver.stg_loans` | 7,663 rows |

Flat fields, `credit_info{}`, and `digital_engagement{}` are merged into `silver.stg_customers` (5,000 rows).

### Deduplication

A window function partitions by the primary key (`customer_id`, `account_id`, `transaction_id`, `loan_id`) and keeps the first occurrence per group. Since Bronze is truncated before each ingestion and the source JSON is a static snapshot, dedup is a safety net rather than a substantive operation.

### Date Normalization

The dataset contains three mixed date formats: `YYYY-MM-DD`, `DD/MM/YYYY`, and `YYYYMMDD`. PySpark detects the format with regex and converts everything to a standard `DATE` type before writing to Silver.

### Writing Silver

Each DataFrame is written to PostgreSQL via JDBC in `overwrite` mode for idempotency.

---

## 8. PowerBI Dashboard

The dashboard has 4 pages connected directly to the `gold` schema. Each page has slicers for `country`, `customer_segment`, and other relevant dimensions.

### Page 1 — Executive Overview

**What it shows:** High-level KPIs — total customers, AUM, active customers, KYC verified rate, customer count by country, monthly acquisition trend, status and KYC distribution, average revenue per segment.

**Business questions answered:** Q1, Q10, Q12, Q13, Q14.

**Decisions it supports:** Strategic overview of the customer base health, acquisition cadence, and segment value.

### Page 2 — Revenue & Transactions

**What it shows:** Transaction volume and value by category (combined chart), transaction count by day of week, average size and revenue by channel, failed rate by channel, international vs local patterns by country, total account balance by country (in USD).

**Business questions answered:** Q2, Q3, Q15, Q16, Q17, Q18, Q19.

**Decisions it supports:** Channel investment priorities, category-level revenue analysis, identification of failure hotspots.

### Page 3 — Risk & Credit

**What it shows:** Delinquency rate by segment, credit score distribution by country, utilization vs delinquency scatter, days past due by loan type, loan portfolio composition (outstanding USD by type and status), interest income by loan type, customer risk segmentation.

**Business questions answered:** Q4, Q5, Q6, Q7, Q8, Q9, Q23.

**Decisions it supports:** Credit risk policy adjustment, portfolio rebalancing, identification of delinquency drivers.

### Page 4 — Customer & Engagement

**What it shows:** Age distribution by segment, mobile app adoption rate by segment, digital vs physical channel preference by age group, account type distribution, average number of products per customer by segment.

**Business questions answered:** Q11, Q20, Q21, Q22, Q24.

**Decisions it supports:** Digital strategy targeting, cross-selling opportunities, product mix optimization.

Screenshots are stored in `powerbi/screenshots/`.

---

## 9. Key Business Insights

### Customer base
- **5,000 customers** distributed across 7 LATAM countries, with **AUM of ~$4,259M USD**.
- Country distribution is balanced (~700 customers per country, range 666–737).
- Customer status is also evenly split: ~25% in each of active, inactive, suspended, closed.

### Revenue & transactions
- **MX leads in total balance** (~$649M USD), followed by PE (~$634M USD) and BR (~$614M USD).
- Total balance differences across countries are now meaningful thanks to USD conversion — comparison in local currency would have been distorted by nominal scale (e.g. COP vs BRL).
- **Failed transaction rate is uniform** across channels (~25% in all channels), suggesting the failure mechanism is not channel-specific in this dataset.
- **54% of transactions are international** — high cross-border activity is a defining feature.

### Risk & credit
- **Delinquency rate is ~50% across all segments** — there is no meaningful differentiation between retail, premium, private banking, and SME. This is a hallmark of the synthetic dataset and would warrant investigation in a real scenario.
- **`poor` credit score is the dominant bucket** (1,733 customers, ~35%), with `unknown` (389) reflecting customers whose `credit_score` was outside the valid 300–850 range and was set to NULL.

### Customer engagement
- **`mobile` is the most popular channel** (1,058 customers), but the distribution across all 5 channels is fairly even.
- **Mobile adoption is ~50% in every segment** — no segment-driven digital adoption pattern.
- The **55+ age bucket is the largest** (~2,033 customers) because it's open-ended; the other buckets cover 10-year spans.

